{"title_page": "Ester H. Segal", "text_new": "{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = Ester H. Segal\n| alma_mater        = [[Technion - Israel Institute of Technology]] (B.Sc, M.Sc, PhD)\n| workplaces        = [[Technion - Israel Institute of Technology]] (2007 - current)\n| website           = \n| known_for         = \n| fields            = [[porous silicon]] \nbiosensors \nfood packaging\n| doctoral_advisor  = Moshe Narkis\n| awards            = \n| image             = \n}}\n'''Ester H. Segal''' is an Israeli [[nanotechnology]] researcher and professor in the Department of Biotechnology and Food Engineering at the [[Technion \u2013 Israel Institute of Technology|Technion - Israel Institute of Technology]], where she heads the Laboratory for Multifunctional Nanomaterials. She is also affiliated with the [[Russell Berrie Nanotechnology Institute]] at the Technion - Israel Institute of Technology.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Ester Segal|url=https://ats.org/about/faces-of-the-technion/ester-segal/|website=American Technion Society|language=en-US|access-date=2020-05-10}}</ref> Segal is best known for her research of [[porous silicon]] nanomaterials, as well as [[nanocomposite]] materials for [[active packaging]] technologies to extend the shelf life of food. In 2019, [[Globes|Lady Globes]] named her one of Israel's top 50 most influential women.<ref name=\":1\" /> Segal is part of the Editorial Advisory Board for the journal ACS Sensors, international advisory board for the Porous Semiconductors Science and Technology biannual conference, and organizing committee member for Israel Society for Biotechnology and Engineering. \n\n== Education ==\nSegal received her bachelor of science degree ''cum laude'' in chemical engineering from the [[Technion \u2013 Israel Institute of Technology|Technion - Israel Institute of Technology]] in 1997. She earned her master of science degree and PhD from the Technion - Israel Institute of Technology in polymer science.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|title=Prof. Ester Segal {{!}} Ester Segal Lab|url=https://segallab.net.technion.ac.il/members/prof-ester-segal/|website=segallab.net.technion.ac.il|access-date=2020-05-10}}</ref>\n\n== Research and career ==\nSegal competed her graduate research with Moshe Narkis at the [[Technion \u2013 Israel Institute of Technology|Technion - Israel Institute of Technology]], where she developed electrically conductive polymer systems and their application as sensors for [[Volatile organic compound|volatile organic compounds]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Segal|first=Ester|last2=Tchoudakov|first2=Roza|last3=Narkis|first3=Moshe|last4=Siegmann|first4=Arnon|last5=Yen Wei|date=2005-01-03|title=Polystyrene/polyaniline nanoblends for sensing of aliphatic alcohols|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0925400504003624|journal=Sensors and Actuators B: Chemical|language=en|volume=104|issue=1|pages=140\u2013150|doi=10.1016/j.snb.2004.05.002|issn=0925-4005}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Jia|first=W.|last2=Segal|first2=E.|last3=Kornemandel|first3=D.|last4=Lamhot|first4=Y.|last5=Narkis|first5=M.|last6=Siegmann|first6=A.|date=2002-04-10|title=Polyaniline\u2013DBSA/organophilic clay nanocomposites: synthesis and characterization|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0379677901006725|journal=Synthetic Metals|language=en|volume=128|issue=1|pages=115\u2013120|doi=10.1016/S0379-6779(01)00672-5|issn=0379-6779}}</ref> After completing her PhD in 2004, Segal was awarded the Rothschild Postdoctoral Fellowship and joined the group of [[Michael J. Sailor]] at the Department of Chemistry and Biochemistry at the [[University of California, San Diego]] from 2004 to 2007. There, she developed [[porous silicon]] nanomaterials for drug delivery and optical biosensing purposes. In 2007, Segal returned to Israel and joined the Department of Biotechnology and Food Engineering at the [[Technion \u2013 Israel Institute of Technology|Technion - Israel Institute of Technology]] to begin her own research lab.<ref name=\":0\" /> She was promoted to the rank of full professor in 2020.  \n\nHer research lab focuses on coupling materials science with chemistry and biotechnology to address problems in food technology and medicine.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Israeli Women Lead The Way In Thriving Biotech Industry {{!}} Health News|url=https://nocamels.com/2020/03/israel-women-biotech-leadership/|date=2020-03-09|website=nocamels.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-05-10}}</ref> Specific areas of in which Segal's research has contributed include optical biosensing, silicon-based therapeutics, silicon-polymer hybrids, and food packaging technologies. \n\n===== Optical biosensors =====\n''Fabry-Perot interferometers''\n\nUsing electrochemical etched mesoporous silicon, Segal's research group has developed label-free, optical sensors by means of [[Fabry\u2013P\u00e9rot interferometer|Fabry-Perot interferometry]]. These sensors, containing pores between 10 and 100 nm have been engineered to detect analytes such as proteins<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Arshavsky-Graham|first=Sofia|last2=Massad-Ivanir|first2=Naama|last3=Paratore|first3=Federico|last4=Scheper|first4=Thomas|last5=Bercovici|first5=Moran|last6=Segal|first6=Ester|date=2017-12-22|title=On Chip Protein Pre-Concentration for Enhancing the Sensitivity of Porous Silicon Biosensors|url=https://doi.org/10.1021/acssensors.7b00692|journal=ACS Sensors|volume=2|issue=12|pages=1767\u20131773|doi=10.1021/acssensors.7b00692}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Urmann|first=Katharina|last2=Reich|first2=Peggy|last3=Walter|first3=Johanna-Gabriela|last4=Beckmann|first4=Dieter|last5=Segal|first5=Ester|last6=Scheper|first6=Thomas|date=2017-09-10|title=Rapid and label-free detection of protein a by aptamer-tethered porous silicon nanostructures|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0168165617300226|journal=Journal of Biotechnology|series=Dedicated to Prof. Dr. Alfred P\u00fchler on the occasion of his 75th birthday|language=en|volume=257|pages=171\u2013177|doi=10.1016/j.jbiotec.2017.01.005|issn=0168-1656}}</ref>, DNA<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Vilensky|first=Rita|last2=Bercovici|first2=Moran|last3=Segal|first3=Ester|date=2015|title=Oxidized Porous Silicon Nanostructures Enabling Electrokinetic Transport for Enhanced DNA Detection|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1002/adfm.201502859|journal=Advanced Functional Materials|language=en|volume=25|issue=43|pages=6725\u20136732|doi=10.1002/adfm.201502859|issn=1616-3028}}</ref>, whole bacteria cells<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Urmann|first=K.|last2=Arshavsky-Graham|first2=S.|last3=Walter|first3=J.|last4=Scheper|first4=T.|last5=Segal|first5=E.|date=2016|title=Whole-cell detection of live lactobacillus acidophilus on aptamer-decorated porous silicon biosensors|url=https://pubs.rsc.org/en/content/articlelanding/2016/an/c6an00810k|journal=Analyst|language=en|volume=141|issue=18|pages=5432\u20135440|doi=10.1039/C6AN00810K|via=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Tenenbaum|first=Elena|last2=Segal|first2=Ester|date=2015-10-26|title=Optical biosensors for bacteria detection by a peptidomimetic antimicrobial compound|url=https://pubs.rsc.org/en/content/articlelanding/2015/an/c5an01717c|journal=Analyst|language=en|volume=140|issue=22|pages=7726\u20137733|doi=10.1039/C5AN01717C|issn=1364-5528}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Massad-Ivanir|first=Naama|last2=Shtenberg|first2=Giorgi|last3=Raz|first3=Nitzan|last4=Gazenbeek|first4=Christel|last5=Budding|first5=Dries|last6=Bos|first6=Martine P.|last7=Segal|first7=Ester|date=2016-11-30|title=Porous Silicon-Based Biosensors: Towards Real-Time Optical Detection of Target Bacteria in the Food Industry|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/srep38099|journal=Scientific Reports|language=en|volume=6|issue=1|pages=1\u201312|doi=10.1038/srep38099|issn=2045-2322}}</ref>, amphipathic molecules on lipid bilayers<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Tenenbaum|first=Elena|last2=Ben-Dov|first2=Nadav|last3=Segal|first3=Ester|date=2015-05-04|title=Tethered Lipid Bilayers within Porous Si Nanostructures: A Platform for (Optical) Real-Time Monitoring of Membrane-Associated Processes|url=https://pubs.acs.org/doi/full/10.1021/acs.langmuir.5b00935|journal=Langmuir|volume=31|issue=18|pages=5244\u20135251|doi=10.1021/acs.langmuir.5b00935|issn=0743-7463}}</ref>, organophosphorus compounds<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Krepker|first=Maksym A.|last2=Segal|first2=Ester|date=2013-08-06|title=Dual-Functionalized Porous Si/Hydrogel Hybrid for Label-Free Biosensing of Organophosphorus Compounds|url=https://doi.org/10.1021/ac4011815|journal=Analytical Chemistry|volume=85|issue=15|pages=7353\u20137360|doi=10.1021/ac4011815|issn=0003-2700}}</ref>, heavy metal ions<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Shtenberg|first=Giorgi|last2=Massad-Ivanir|first2=Naama|last3=Segal|first3=Ester|date=2015-06-15|title=Detection of trace heavy metal ions in water by nanostructured porous Si biosensors|url=https://pubs.rsc.org/en/content/articlelanding/2015/an/c5an00248f|journal=Analyst|language=en|volume=140|issue=13|pages=4507\u20134514|doi=10.1039/C5AN00248F|issn=1364-5528}}</ref>, and proteolytic products from enzymatic activity<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Shtenberg|first=Giorgi|last2=Massad-Ivanir|first2=Naama|last3=Moscovitz|first3=Oren|last4=Engin|first4=Sinem|last5=Sharon|first5=Michal|last6=Fruk|first6=Ljiljana|last7=Segal|first7=Ester|date=2013-02-05|title=Picking up the Pieces: A Generic Porous Si Biosensor for Probing the Proteolytic Products of Enzymes|url=https://doi.org/10.1021/ac303597w|journal=Analytical Chemistry|volume=85|issue=3|pages=1951\u20131956|doi=10.1021/ac303597w|issn=0003-2700}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Shtenberg|first=Giorgi|last2=Massad-Ivanir|first2=Naama|last3=Engin|first3=Sinem|last4=Sharon|first4=Michal|last5=Fruk|first5=Ljiljana|last6=Segal|first6=Ester|date=2012-08-08|title=DNA-directed immobilization of horseradish peroxidase onto porous SiO2 optical transducers|url=https://doi.org/10.1186/1556-276X-7-443|journal=Nanoscale Research Letters|language=en|volume=7|issue=1|pages=443|doi=10.1186/1556-276X-7-443|issn=1556-276X|pmc=3479059|pmid=22873686}}</ref>. Some of Segal's sensors have been integrated with [[isotachophoresis]] and/or engineered with specific surface functionalizations (e.g. attached proteins, enzymes, aptamers, and antimicrobial peptides) to enhance the [[Detection limit|limits of detection]] for certain analytes. Segal has helped engineer hybrid porous silicon materials for sensing purposes, including carbon dot-infused silicon transducers<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Massad-Ivanir|first=Naama|last2=Bhunia|first2=Susanta Kumar|last3=Raz|first3=Nitzan|last4=Segal|first4=Ester|last5=Jelinek|first5=Raz|date=2018|title=Synthesis and characterization of a nanostructured porous silicon/carbon dot-hybrid for orthogonal molecular detection|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/am2017233|journal=NPG Asia Materials|language=en|volume=10|issue=1|pages=e463\u2013e463|doi=10.1038/am.2017.233|issn=1884-4057|via=}}</ref>, hydrogel-confined silicon substrates<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Massad\u2010Ivanir|first=Naama|last2=Shtenberg|first2=Giorgi|last3=Zeidman|first3=Tal|last4=Segal|first4=Ester|date=2010|title=Construction and Characterization of Porous SiO2/Hydrogel Hybrids as Optical Biosensors for Rapid Detection of Bacteria|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1002/adfm.201000406|journal=Advanced Functional Materials|language=en|volume=20|issue=14|pages=2269\u20132277|doi=10.1002/adfm.201000406|issn=1616-3028}}</ref>, and polymer-silicon hybrids<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bussi|first=Yonit|last2=Holtzman|first2=Liran|last3=Shagan|first3=Alona|last4=Segal|first4=Ester|last5=Mizrahi|first5=Boaz|date=2017|title=Light-triggered antifouling coatings for porous silicon optical transducers|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1002/pat.3989|journal=Polymers for Advanced Technologies|language=en|volume=28|issue=7|pages=859\u2013866|doi=10.1002/pat.3989|issn=1099-1581}}</ref>. \n\n''Diffraction gratings''\n\nSegal's research group engineered microstructured silicon optical sensors for the detection and monitoring of microorganisms, including bacteria and fungi, in both clinical samples and food.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Massad-Ivanir|first=Naama|last2=Mirsky|first2=Yossi|last3=Nahor|first3=Amit|last4=Edrei|first4=Eitan|last5=Bonanno-Young|first5=Lisa M.|last6=Dov|first6=Nadav Ben|last7=Sa'ar|first7=Amir|last8=Segal|first8=Ester|date=2014-07-14|title=Trap and track: designing self-reporting porous Si photonic crystals for rapid bacteria detection|url=https://pubs.rsc.org/en/content/articlelanding/2014/an/c4an00364k|journal=Analyst|language=en|volume=139|issue=16|pages=3885\u20133894|doi=10.1039/C4AN00364K|issn=1364-5528}}</ref> The microstructured substrates serve as reflective [[Diffraction grating|diffraction gratings]] for label-free measurements of [[refractive index]].<ref>{{Cite patent|title=Method and apparatus for bacterial monitoring|gdate=2014-03-25|url=https://patents.google.com/patent/US10309958B2/en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite patent|title=Methods of determining cellular phenotypes|gdate=2016-03-09|url=https://patents.google.com/patent/US10281463B2/en}}</ref> By tracking bacterial growth in response to antibiotics, Segal's group (in collaboration with the Department of Urology at the [[Bnai Zion Medical Center|Bnai Zion hospital]] and [[HaEmek Medical Center|Ha'Emek Medical Center]]) developed a means of rapid antimicrobial susceptibility testing for clinical samples.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Leonard|first=Heidi|last2=Halachmi|first2=Sarel|last3=Ben-Dov|first3=Nadav|last4=Nativ|first4=Ofer|last5=Segal|first5=Ester|date=2017-06-27|title=Unraveling Antimicrobial Susceptibility of Bacterial Networks on Micropillar Architectures Using Intrinsic Phase-Shift Spectroscopy|url=https://doi.org/10.1021/acsnano.7b02217|journal=ACS Nano|volume=11|issue=6|pages=6167\u20136177|doi=10.1021/acsnano.7b02217|issn=1936-0851}}</ref>\n\n===== Porous silicon therapeutics =====\nSegal and her research team engineered porous silicon carriers containing [[nerve growth factor]] for delivery to the brain in Alzheimer's models<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Zilony\u2010Hanin|first=Neta|last2=Rosenberg|first2=Michal|last3=Richman|first3=Michal|last4=Yehuda|first4=Ronen|last5=Schori|first5=Hadas|last6=Motiei|first6=Menachem|last7=Rahimipour|first7=Shai|last8=Groisman|first8=Alexander|last9=Segal|first9=Ester|last10=Shefi|first10=Orit|date=2019|title=Neuroprotective Effect of Nerve Growth Factor Loaded in Porous Silicon Nanostructures in an Alzheimer's Disease Model and Potential Delivery to the Brain|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1002/smll.201904203|journal=Small|language=en|volume=15|issue=45|pages=1904203|doi=10.1002/smll.201904203|issn=1613-6829}}</ref>, in addition to carriers of anti-cancer drugs to diseased tissue<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Tzur-Balter|first=Adi|last2=Rubinski|first2=Anna|last3=Segal|first3=Ester|date=2013|title=Designing porous silicon-based microparticles as carriers for controlled delivery of mitoxantrone dihydrochloride|url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/journal-of-materials-research/article/designing-porous-siliconbased-microparticles-as-carriers-for-controlled-delivery-of-mitoxantrone-dihydrochloride/67698F24195B5FD67F563AB38A67D473|journal=Journal of Materials Research|language=en|volume=28|issue=2|pages=231\u2013239|doi=10.1557/jmr.2012.299|issn=0884-2914|via=}}</ref> and [[bone morphogenetic protein 2]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Rosenberg|first=Michal|last2=Shilo|first2=Dekel|last3=Galperin|first3=Leonid|last4=Capucha|first4=Tal|last5=Tarabieh|first5=Karim|last6=Rachmiel|first6=Adi|last7=Segal|first7=Ester|date=2019|title=Bone Morphogenic Protein 2-Loaded Porous Silicon Carriers for Osteoinductive Implants|url=https://www.mdpi.com/1999-4923/11/11/602|journal=Pharmaceutics|language=en|volume=11|issue=11|pages=602|doi=10.3390/pharmaceutics11110602|via=}}</ref> She also demonstrated the delivery of anti-cancer drugs captured in silicon microparticles with a [[Gene gun|pneumatic capillary gene gun]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Zilony|first=Neta|last2=Tzur-Balter|first2=Adi|last3=Segal|first3=Ester|last4=Shefi|first4=Orit|date=2013-08-26|title=Bombarding Cancer: Biolistic Delivery of therapeutics using Porous Si Carriers|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/srep02499|journal=Scientific Reports|language=en|volume=3|issue=1|pages=1\u20136|doi=10.1038/srep02499|issn=2045-2322}}</ref> She has studied the kinetics and degradation of porous silicon therapeutics in disease models,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Tzur-Balter|first=Adi|last2=Young|first2=Jonathan M.|last3=Bonanno-Young|first3=Lisa M.|last4=Segal|first4=Ester|date=2013-09-01|title=Mathematical modeling of drug release from nanostructured porous Si: Combining carrier erosion and hindered drug diffusion for predicting release kinetics|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1742706113002912|journal=Acta Biomaterialia|language=en|volume=9|issue=9|pages=8346\u20138353|doi=10.1016/j.actbio.2013.06.007|issn=1742-7061}}</ref> finding that porous silicon materials tend to degrade at faster rates in diseased tissue environments compared to healthy tissue.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Tzur-Balter|first=Adi|last2=Shatsberg|first2=Zohar|last3=Beckerman|first3=Margarita|last4=Segal|first4=Ester|last5=Artzi|first5=Natalie|date=2015-02-11|title=Mechanism of erosion of nanostructured porous silicon drug carriers in neoplastic tissues|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/ncomms7208|journal=Nature Communications|language=en|volume=6|issue=1|pages=1\u20138|doi=10.1038/ncomms7208|issn=2041-1723}}</ref>\n\n===== Food packaging technologies =====\nIn contrast to the research on silicon nanomaterials, a large part of Segal's research focuses on the development of new technologies for active packaging of food usually through the incorporation of polymers, nanomaterials, and essential oils.<ref>{{Cite patent|title=Hollow mineral tubes comprising essential oils and uses thereof|gdate=2016-03-24|url=https://patents.google.com/patent/WO2016151593A1/en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Krepker|first=Maksym|last2=Shemesh|first2=Rotem|last3=Danin Poleg|first3=Yael|last4=Kashi|first4=Yechezkel|last5=Vaxman|first5=Anita|last6=Segal|first6=Ester|date=2017-06-01|title=Active food packaging films with synergistic antimicrobial activity|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0956713517300245|journal=Food Control|language=en|volume=76|pages=117\u2013126|doi=10.1016/j.foodcont.2017.01.014|issn=0956-7135}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Krepker|first=Max|last2=Zhang|first2=Cong|last3=Nitzan|first3=Nadav|last4=Prinz-Setter|first4=Ofer|last5=Massad-Ivanir|first5=Naama|last6=Olah|first6=Andrew|last7=Baer|first7=Eric|last8=Segal|first8=Ester|date=2018|title=Antimicrobial LDPE/EVOH Layered Films Containing Carvacrol Fabricated by Multiplication Extrusion|url=https://www.mdpi.com/2073-4360/10/8/864|journal=Polymers|language=en|volume=10|issue=8|pages=864|doi=10.3390/polym10080864|via=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Shemesh|first=Rotem|last2=Goldman|first2=Diana|last3=Krepker|first3=Maksym|last4=Danin\u2010Poleg|first4=Yael|last5=Kashi|first5=Yechezkel|last6=Vaxman|first6=Anita|last7=Segal|first7=Ester|date=2015|title=LDPE/clay/carvacrol nanocomposites with prolonged antimicrobial activity|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1002/app.41261|journal=Journal of Applied Polymer Science|language=en|volume=132|issue=2|doi=10.1002/app.41261|issn=1097-4628}}</ref> These materials have antimicrobial properties, allowing them to preserve food for longer times, and in turn, reducing food waste.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Shemesh|first=Rotem|last2=Krepker|first2=Maksym|last3=Nitzan|first3=Nadav|last4=Vaxman|first4=Anita|last5=Segal|first5=Ester|date=2016-08-01|title=Active packaging containing encapsulated carvacrol for control of postharvest decay|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0925521416300680|journal=Postharvest Biology and Technology|language=en|volume=118|pages=175\u2013182|doi=10.1016/j.postharvbio.2016.04.009|issn=0925-5214}}</ref>\n\n== Awards ==\n\n* 2019 ACS Advances in Measurement Science Lectureship Award for her work on photonic crystal sensing.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Pittcon|url=https://acsanalytical.org/pittcon/|date=2017-06-19|website=ACS Division of Analytical Chemistry|language=en-US|access-date=2020-05-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=Announcing the 2019 Advances in Measurement Science Lectureship Award Winners|url=https://axial.acs.org/2019/01/11/announcing-the-2019-advances-in-measurement-science-lectureship-award-winners/|date=2019-01-11|website=ACS Axial|language=en-US|access-date=2020-05-11}}</ref>\n*2019 Lady Globes named her one of Israel's top 50 most influential women<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|title=\u05dc\u05d9\u05d9\u05d3\u05d9 \u05d2\u05dc\u05d5\u05d1\u05e1 \u05de\u05e6\u05d9\u05d2: 50 \u05d4\u05de\u05e9\u05e4\u05d9\u05e2\u05d5\u05ea 2019 - \u05e4\u05e8\u05d5\u05e4\u2019 \u05e0\u05d9\u05e8\u05d9\u05ea \u05d3\u05d5\u05d3\u05d5\u05d1\u05d9\u05e5|url=https://www.globes.co.il/news/article.aspx?did=1001300539|website=\u05d2\u05dc\u05d5\u05d1\u05e1|language=he|access-date=2020-05-10}}</ref>\n*2017 Discovery Award for Team Prismatix (part of UK Longitude Prize Contest) antimicrobial resistance testing technology\n*2016 Hershel Rich Innovation Award\n*2016 Daniel Shiran Memorial Research Prize for outstanding research in biomedicine\n*2015 Yanai Prize for Excellence in Academic Education\n*2014 Henry Taub Award for Academic Excellence\n*2009, 2010, 2011, 2012, 2013, 2014, 2015, 2016, 2017 Technion Excellence in Teaching Award\n\n== Entrepreneurship ==\nSegal serves as the CTO to BactuSense Technologies Ltd and was the project coordinator of Nanopak, an EU-funded project that developed food packaging products in order to extend the shelf life of food.<ref>{{Cite web|title=NanoPack\u2019s Active Food Packaging Shows Impressive Results in Extending Food Shelf Life: (EUFIC)|url=https://www.eufic.org/en/newsroom/article/nanopacks-active-food-packaging-shows-impressive-results-in-extending-food-shelf-life|website=www.eufic.org|access-date=2020-05-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=Home|url=https://www.nanopack.eu/|last=Care|first=Update|website=NanoPack|language=en-US|access-date=2020-05-10}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nSegal is a cancer survivor,<ref>{{Cite web|title=Engineering meets medicine for maximum impact|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/spotlight/engineering-meets-medicine-for-maximum-impact/|last=Society|first=Jennifer Frey-American Technion|website=www.timesofisrael.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-05-10}}</ref> married, and has two children.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Segal, Ester H.}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Technion \u2013 Israel Institute of Technology alumni]]\n[[Category:Technion \u2013 Israel Institute of Technology faculty]]\n[[Category:Nanotechnologists]]\n[[Category:Israeli women engineers]]\n[[Category:Israeli chemical engineers]]\n[[Category:Polymer scientists and engineers]]\n", "text_old": "__INDEX__\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = Ester H. Segal\n| alma_mater        = [[Technion - Israel Institute of Technology]] (B.Sc, M.Sc, PhD)\n| workplaces        = [[Technion - Israel Institute of Technology]] (2007 - current)\n| website           = \n| known_for         = \n| fields            = [[porous silicon]] \nbiosensors \nfood packaging\n| doctoral_advisor  = Moshe Narkis\n| awards            = \n| image             = \n}}\n'''Ester H. Segal''' is an Israeli [[nanotechnology]] researcher and professor in the Department of Biotechnology and Food Engineering at the [[Technion \u2013 Israel Institute of Technology|Technion - Israel Institute of Technology]], where she heads the Laboratory for Multifunctional Nanomaterials. She is also affiliated with the [[Russell Berrie Nanotechnology Institute]] at the Technion - Israel Institute of Technology.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Ester Segal|url=https://ats.org/about/faces-of-the-technion/ester-segal/|website=American Technion Society|language=en-US|access-date=2020-05-10}}</ref> Segal is best known for her research of [[porous silicon]] nanomaterials, as well as [[nanocomposite]] materials for [[active packaging]] technologies to extend the shelf life of food. In 2019, [[Globes|Lady Globes]] named her one of Israel's top 50 most influential women.<ref name=\":1\" /> Segal is part of the Editorial Advisory Board for the journal ACS Sensors, international advisory board for the Porous Semiconductors Science and Technology biannual conference, and organizing committee member for Israel Society for Biotechnology and Engineering. \n\n== Education ==\nSegal received her bachelor of science degree ''cum laude'' in chemical engineering from the [[Technion \u2013 Israel Institute of Technology|Technion - Israel Institute of Technology]] in 1997. She earned her master of science degree and PhD from the Technion - Israel Institute of Technology in polymer science.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|title=Prof. Ester Segal {{!}} Ester Segal Lab|url=https://segallab.net.technion.ac.il/members/prof-ester-segal/|website=segallab.net.technion.ac.il|access-date=2020-05-10}}</ref>\n\n== Research and career ==\nSegal competed her graduate research with Moshe Narkis at the [[Technion \u2013 Israel Institute of Technology|Technion - Israel Institute of Technology]], where she developed electrically conductive polymer systems and their application as sensors for [[Volatile organic compound|volatile organic compounds]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Segal|first=Ester|last2=Tchoudakov|first2=Roza|last3=Narkis|first3=Moshe|last4=Siegmann|first4=Arnon|last5=Yen Wei|date=2005-01-03|title=Polystyrene/polyaniline nanoblends for sensing of aliphatic alcohols|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0925400504003624|journal=Sensors and Actuators B: Chemical|language=en|volume=104|issue=1|pages=140\u2013150|doi=10.1016/j.snb.2004.05.002|issn=0925-4005}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Jia|first=W.|last2=Segal|first2=E.|last3=Kornemandel|first3=D.|last4=Lamhot|first4=Y.|last5=Narkis|first5=M.|last6=Siegmann|first6=A.|date=2002-04-10|title=Polyaniline\u2013DBSA/organophilic clay nanocomposites: synthesis and characterization|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0379677901006725|journal=Synthetic Metals|language=en|volume=128|issue=1|pages=115\u2013120|doi=10.1016/S0379-6779(01)00672-5|issn=0379-6779}}</ref> After completing her PhD in 2004, Segal was awarded the Rothschild Postdoctoral Fellowship and joined the group of [[Michael J. Sailor]] at the Department of Chemistry and Biochemistry at the [[University of California, San Diego]] from 2004 to 2007. There, she developed [[porous silicon]] nanomaterials for drug delivery and optical biosensing purposes. In 2007, Segal returned to Israel and joined the Department of Biotechnology and Food Engineering at the [[Technion \u2013 Israel Institute of Technology|Technion - Israel Institute of Technology]] to begin her own research lab.<ref name=\":0\" /> She was promoted to the rank of full professor in 2020.  \n\nHer research lab focuses on coupling materials science with chemistry and biotechnology to address problems in food technology and medicine.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Israeli Women Lead The Way In Thriving Biotech Industry {{!}} Health News|url=https://nocamels.com/2020/03/israel-women-biotech-leadership/|date=2020-03-09|website=nocamels.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-05-10}}</ref> Specific areas of in which Segal's research has contributed include optical biosensing, silicon-based therapeutics, silicon-polymer hybrids, and food packaging technologies. \n\n===== Optical biosensors =====\n''Fabry-Perot interferometers''\n\nUsing electrochemical etched mesoporous silicon, Segal's research group has developed label-free, optical sensors by means of [[Fabry\u2013P\u00e9rot interferometer|Fabry-Perot interferometry]]. These sensors, containing pores between 10 and 100 nm have been engineered to detect analytes such as proteins<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Arshavsky-Graham|first=Sofia|last2=Massad-Ivanir|first2=Naama|last3=Paratore|first3=Federico|last4=Scheper|first4=Thomas|last5=Bercovici|first5=Moran|last6=Segal|first6=Ester|date=2017-12-22|title=On Chip Protein Pre-Concentration for Enhancing the Sensitivity of Porous Silicon Biosensors|url=https://doi.org/10.1021/acssensors.7b00692|journal=ACS Sensors|volume=2|issue=12|pages=1767\u20131773|doi=10.1021/acssensors.7b00692}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Urmann|first=Katharina|last2=Reich|first2=Peggy|last3=Walter|first3=Johanna-Gabriela|last4=Beckmann|first4=Dieter|last5=Segal|first5=Ester|last6=Scheper|first6=Thomas|date=2017-09-10|title=Rapid and label-free detection of protein a by aptamer-tethered porous silicon nanostructures|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0168165617300226|journal=Journal of Biotechnology|series=Dedicated to Prof. Dr. Alfred P\u00fchler on the occasion of his 75th birthday|language=en|volume=257|pages=171\u2013177|doi=10.1016/j.jbiotec.2017.01.005|issn=0168-1656}}</ref>, DNA<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Vilensky|first=Rita|last2=Bercovici|first2=Moran|last3=Segal|first3=Ester|date=2015|title=Oxidized Porous Silicon Nanostructures Enabling Electrokinetic Transport for Enhanced DNA Detection|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1002/adfm.201502859|journal=Advanced Functional Materials|language=en|volume=25|issue=43|pages=6725\u20136732|doi=10.1002/adfm.201502859|issn=1616-3028}}</ref>, whole bacteria cells<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Urmann|first=K.|last2=Arshavsky-Graham|first2=S.|last3=Walter|first3=J.|last4=Scheper|first4=T.|last5=Segal|first5=E.|date=2016|title=Whole-cell detection of live lactobacillus acidophilus on aptamer-decorated porous silicon biosensors|url=https://pubs.rsc.org/en/content/articlelanding/2016/an/c6an00810k|journal=Analyst|language=en|volume=141|issue=18|pages=5432\u20135440|doi=10.1039/C6AN00810K|via=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Tenenbaum|first=Elena|last2=Segal|first2=Ester|date=2015-10-26|title=Optical biosensors for bacteria detection by a peptidomimetic antimicrobial compound|url=https://pubs.rsc.org/en/content/articlelanding/2015/an/c5an01717c|journal=Analyst|language=en|volume=140|issue=22|pages=7726\u20137733|doi=10.1039/C5AN01717C|issn=1364-5528}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Massad-Ivanir|first=Naama|last2=Shtenberg|first2=Giorgi|last3=Raz|first3=Nitzan|last4=Gazenbeek|first4=Christel|last5=Budding|first5=Dries|last6=Bos|first6=Martine P.|last7=Segal|first7=Ester|date=2016-11-30|title=Porous Silicon-Based Biosensors: Towards Real-Time Optical Detection of Target Bacteria in the Food Industry|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/srep38099|journal=Scientific Reports|language=en|volume=6|issue=1|pages=1\u201312|doi=10.1038/srep38099|issn=2045-2322}}</ref>, amphipathic molecules on lipid bilayers<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Tenenbaum|first=Elena|last2=Ben-Dov|first2=Nadav|last3=Segal|first3=Ester|date=2015-05-04|title=Tethered Lipid Bilayers within Porous Si Nanostructures: A Platform for (Optical) Real-Time Monitoring of Membrane-Associated Processes|url=https://pubs.acs.org/doi/full/10.1021/acs.langmuir.5b00935|journal=Langmuir|volume=31|issue=18|pages=5244\u20135251|doi=10.1021/acs.langmuir.5b00935|issn=0743-7463}}</ref>, organophosphorus compounds<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Krepker|first=Maksym A.|last2=Segal|first2=Ester|date=2013-08-06|title=Dual-Functionalized Porous Si/Hydrogel Hybrid for Label-Free Biosensing of Organophosphorus Compounds|url=https://doi.org/10.1021/ac4011815|journal=Analytical Chemistry|volume=85|issue=15|pages=7353\u20137360|doi=10.1021/ac4011815|issn=0003-2700}}</ref>, heavy metal ions<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Shtenberg|first=Giorgi|last2=Massad-Ivanir|first2=Naama|last3=Segal|first3=Ester|date=2015-06-15|title=Detection of trace heavy metal ions in water by nanostructured porous Si biosensors|url=https://pubs.rsc.org/en/content/articlelanding/2015/an/c5an00248f|journal=Analyst|language=en|volume=140|issue=13|pages=4507\u20134514|doi=10.1039/C5AN00248F|issn=1364-5528}}</ref>, and proteolytic products from enzymatic activity<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Shtenberg|first=Giorgi|last2=Massad-Ivanir|first2=Naama|last3=Moscovitz|first3=Oren|last4=Engin|first4=Sinem|last5=Sharon|first5=Michal|last6=Fruk|first6=Ljiljana|last7=Segal|first7=Ester|date=2013-02-05|title=Picking up the Pieces: A Generic Porous Si Biosensor for Probing the Proteolytic Products of Enzymes|url=https://doi.org/10.1021/ac303597w|journal=Analytical Chemistry|volume=85|issue=3|pages=1951\u20131956|doi=10.1021/ac303597w|issn=0003-2700}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Shtenberg|first=Giorgi|last2=Massad-Ivanir|first2=Naama|last3=Engin|first3=Sinem|last4=Sharon|first4=Michal|last5=Fruk|first5=Ljiljana|last6=Segal|first6=Ester|date=2012-08-08|title=DNA-directed immobilization of horseradish peroxidase onto porous SiO2 optical transducers|url=https://doi.org/10.1186/1556-276X-7-443|journal=Nanoscale Research Letters|language=en|volume=7|issue=1|pages=443|doi=10.1186/1556-276X-7-443|issn=1556-276X|pmc=3479059|pmid=22873686}}</ref>. Some of Segal's sensors have been integrated with [[isotachophoresis]] and/or engineered with specific surface functionalizations (e.g. attached proteins, enzymes, aptamers, and antimicrobial peptides) to enhance the [[Detection limit|limits of detection]] for certain analytes. Segal has helped engineer hybrid porous silicon materials for sensing purposes, including carbon dot-infused silicon transducers<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Massad-Ivanir|first=Naama|last2=Bhunia|first2=Susanta Kumar|last3=Raz|first3=Nitzan|last4=Segal|first4=Ester|last5=Jelinek|first5=Raz|date=2018|title=Synthesis and characterization of a nanostructured porous silicon/carbon dot-hybrid for orthogonal molecular detection|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/am2017233|journal=NPG Asia Materials|language=en|volume=10|issue=1|pages=e463\u2013e463|doi=10.1038/am.2017.233|issn=1884-4057|via=}}</ref>, hydrogel-confined silicon substrates<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Massad\u2010Ivanir|first=Naama|last2=Shtenberg|first2=Giorgi|last3=Zeidman|first3=Tal|last4=Segal|first4=Ester|date=2010|title=Construction and Characterization of Porous SiO2/Hydrogel Hybrids as Optical Biosensors for Rapid Detection of Bacteria|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1002/adfm.201000406|journal=Advanced Functional Materials|language=en|volume=20|issue=14|pages=2269\u20132277|doi=10.1002/adfm.201000406|issn=1616-3028}}</ref>, and polymer-silicon hybrids<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bussi|first=Yonit|last2=Holtzman|first2=Liran|last3=Shagan|first3=Alona|last4=Segal|first4=Ester|last5=Mizrahi|first5=Boaz|date=2017|title=Light-triggered antifouling coatings for porous silicon optical transducers|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1002/pat.3989|journal=Polymers for Advanced Technologies|language=en|volume=28|issue=7|pages=859\u2013866|doi=10.1002/pat.3989|issn=1099-1581}}</ref>. \n\n''Diffraction gratings''\n\nSegal's research group engineered microstructured silicon optical sensors for the detection and monitoring of microorganisms, including bacteria and fungi, in both clinical samples and food.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Massad-Ivanir|first=Naama|last2=Mirsky|first2=Yossi|last3=Nahor|first3=Amit|last4=Edrei|first4=Eitan|last5=Bonanno-Young|first5=Lisa M.|last6=Dov|first6=Nadav Ben|last7=Sa'ar|first7=Amir|last8=Segal|first8=Ester|date=2014-07-14|title=Trap and track: designing self-reporting porous Si photonic crystals for rapid bacteria detection|url=https://pubs.rsc.org/en/content/articlelanding/2014/an/c4an00364k|journal=Analyst|language=en|volume=139|issue=16|pages=3885\u20133894|doi=10.1039/C4AN00364K|issn=1364-5528}}</ref> The microstructured substrates serve as reflective [[Diffraction grating|diffraction gratings]] for label-free measurements of [[refractive index]].<ref>{{Cite patent|title=Method and apparatus for bacterial monitoring|gdate=2014-03-25|url=https://patents.google.com/patent/US10309958B2/en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite patent|title=Methods of determining cellular phenotypes|gdate=2016-03-09|url=https://patents.google.com/patent/US10281463B2/en}}</ref> By tracking bacterial growth in response to antibiotics, Segal's group (in collaboration with the Department of Urology at the [[Bnai Zion Medical Center|Bnai Zion hospital]] and [[HaEmek Medical Center|Ha'Emek Medical Center]]) developed a means of rapid antimicrobial susceptibility testing for clinical samples.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Leonard|first=Heidi|last2=Halachmi|first2=Sarel|last3=Ben-Dov|first3=Nadav|last4=Nativ|first4=Ofer|last5=Segal|first5=Ester|date=2017-06-27|title=Unraveling Antimicrobial Susceptibility of Bacterial Networks on Micropillar Architectures Using Intrinsic Phase-Shift Spectroscopy|url=https://doi.org/10.1021/acsnano.7b02217|journal=ACS Nano|volume=11|issue=6|pages=6167\u20136177|doi=10.1021/acsnano.7b02217|issn=1936-0851}}</ref>\n\n===== Porous silicon therapeutics =====\nSegal and her research team engineered porous silicon carriers containing [[nerve growth factor]] for delivery to the brain in Alzheimer's models<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Zilony\u2010Hanin|first=Neta|last2=Rosenberg|first2=Michal|last3=Richman|first3=Michal|last4=Yehuda|first4=Ronen|last5=Schori|first5=Hadas|last6=Motiei|first6=Menachem|last7=Rahimipour|first7=Shai|last8=Groisman|first8=Alexander|last9=Segal|first9=Ester|last10=Shefi|first10=Orit|date=2019|title=Neuroprotective Effect of Nerve Growth Factor Loaded in Porous Silicon Nanostructures in an Alzheimer's Disease Model and Potential Delivery to the Brain|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1002/smll.201904203|journal=Small|language=en|volume=15|issue=45|pages=1904203|doi=10.1002/smll.201904203|issn=1613-6829}}</ref>, in addition to carriers of anti-cancer drugs to diseased tissue<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Tzur-Balter|first=Adi|last2=Rubinski|first2=Anna|last3=Segal|first3=Ester|date=2013|title=Designing porous silicon-based microparticles as carriers for controlled delivery of mitoxantrone dihydrochloride|url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/journal-of-materials-research/article/designing-porous-siliconbased-microparticles-as-carriers-for-controlled-delivery-of-mitoxantrone-dihydrochloride/67698F24195B5FD67F563AB38A67D473|journal=Journal of Materials Research|language=en|volume=28|issue=2|pages=231\u2013239|doi=10.1557/jmr.2012.299|issn=0884-2914|via=}}</ref> and [[bone morphogenetic protein 2]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Rosenberg|first=Michal|last2=Shilo|first2=Dekel|last3=Galperin|first3=Leonid|last4=Capucha|first4=Tal|last5=Tarabieh|first5=Karim|last6=Rachmiel|first6=Adi|last7=Segal|first7=Ester|date=2019|title=Bone Morphogenic Protein 2-Loaded Porous Silicon Carriers for Osteoinductive Implants|url=https://www.mdpi.com/1999-4923/11/11/602|journal=Pharmaceutics|language=en|volume=11|issue=11|pages=602|doi=10.3390/pharmaceutics11110602|via=}}</ref> She also demonstrated the delivery of anti-cancer drugs captured in silicon microparticles with a [[Gene gun|pneumatic capillary gene gun]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Zilony|first=Neta|last2=Tzur-Balter|first2=Adi|last3=Segal|first3=Ester|last4=Shefi|first4=Orit|date=2013-08-26|title=Bombarding Cancer: Biolistic Delivery of therapeutics using Porous Si Carriers|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/srep02499|journal=Scientific Reports|language=en|volume=3|issue=1|pages=1\u20136|doi=10.1038/srep02499|issn=2045-2322}}</ref> She has studied the kinetics and degradation of porous silicon therapeutics in disease models,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Tzur-Balter|first=Adi|last2=Young|first2=Jonathan M.|last3=Bonanno-Young|first3=Lisa M.|last4=Segal|first4=Ester|date=2013-09-01|title=Mathematical modeling of drug release from nanostructured porous Si: Combining carrier erosion and hindered drug diffusion for predicting release kinetics|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1742706113002912|journal=Acta Biomaterialia|language=en|volume=9|issue=9|pages=8346\u20138353|doi=10.1016/j.actbio.2013.06.007|issn=1742-7061}}</ref> finding that porous silicon materials tend to degrade at faster rates in diseased tissue environments compared to healthy tissue.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Tzur-Balter|first=Adi|last2=Shatsberg|first2=Zohar|last3=Beckerman|first3=Margarita|last4=Segal|first4=Ester|last5=Artzi|first5=Natalie|date=2015-02-11|title=Mechanism of erosion of nanostructured porous silicon drug carriers in neoplastic tissues|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/ncomms7208|journal=Nature Communications|language=en|volume=6|issue=1|pages=1\u20138|doi=10.1038/ncomms7208|issn=2041-1723}}</ref>\n\n===== Food packaging technologies =====\nIn contrast to the research on silicon nanomaterials, a large part of Segal's research focuses on the development of new technologies for active packaging of food usually through the incorporation of polymers, nanomaterials, and essential oils.<ref>{{Cite patent|title=Hollow mineral tubes comprising essential oils and uses thereof|gdate=2016-03-24|url=https://patents.google.com/patent/WO2016151593A1/en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Krepker|first=Maksym|last2=Shemesh|first2=Rotem|last3=Danin Poleg|first3=Yael|last4=Kashi|first4=Yechezkel|last5=Vaxman|first5=Anita|last6=Segal|first6=Ester|date=2017-06-01|title=Active food packaging films with synergistic antimicrobial activity|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0956713517300245|journal=Food Control|language=en|volume=76|pages=117\u2013126|doi=10.1016/j.foodcont.2017.01.014|issn=0956-7135}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Krepker|first=Max|last2=Zhang|first2=Cong|last3=Nitzan|first3=Nadav|last4=Prinz-Setter|first4=Ofer|last5=Massad-Ivanir|first5=Naama|last6=Olah|first6=Andrew|last7=Baer|first7=Eric|last8=Segal|first8=Ester|date=2018|title=Antimicrobial LDPE/EVOH Layered Films Containing Carvacrol Fabricated by Multiplication Extrusion|url=https://www.mdpi.com/2073-4360/10/8/864|journal=Polymers|language=en|volume=10|issue=8|pages=864|doi=10.3390/polym10080864|via=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Shemesh|first=Rotem|last2=Goldman|first2=Diana|last3=Krepker|first3=Maksym|last4=Danin\u2010Poleg|first4=Yael|last5=Kashi|first5=Yechezkel|last6=Vaxman|first6=Anita|last7=Segal|first7=Ester|date=2015|title=LDPE/clay/carvacrol nanocomposites with prolonged antimicrobial activity|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1002/app.41261|journal=Journal of Applied Polymer Science|language=en|volume=132|issue=2|doi=10.1002/app.41261|issn=1097-4628}}</ref> These materials have antimicrobial properties, allowing them to preserve food for longer times, and in turn, reducing food waste.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Shemesh|first=Rotem|last2=Krepker|first2=Maksym|last3=Nitzan|first3=Nadav|last4=Vaxman|first4=Anita|last5=Segal|first5=Ester|date=2016-08-01|title=Active packaging containing encapsulated carvacrol for control of postharvest decay|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0925521416300680|journal=Postharvest Biology and Technology|language=en|volume=118|pages=175\u2013182|doi=10.1016/j.postharvbio.2016.04.009|issn=0925-5214}}</ref>\n\n== Awards ==\n\n* 2019 ACS Advances in Measurement Science Lectureship Award for her work on photonic crystal sensing.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Pittcon|url=https://acsanalytical.org/pittcon/|date=2017-06-19|website=ACS Division of Analytical Chemistry|language=en-US|access-date=2020-05-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=Announcing the 2019 Advances in Measurement Science Lectureship Award Winners|url=https://axial.acs.org/2019/01/11/announcing-the-2019-advances-in-measurement-science-lectureship-award-winners/|date=2019-01-11|website=ACS Axial|language=en-US|access-date=2020-05-11}}</ref>\n*2019 Lady Globes named her one of Israel's top 50 most influential women<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|title=\u05dc\u05d9\u05d9\u05d3\u05d9 \u05d2\u05dc\u05d5\u05d1\u05e1 \u05de\u05e6\u05d9\u05d2: 50 \u05d4\u05de\u05e9\u05e4\u05d9\u05e2\u05d5\u05ea 2019 - \u05e4\u05e8\u05d5\u05e4\u2019 \u05e0\u05d9\u05e8\u05d9\u05ea \u05d3\u05d5\u05d3\u05d5\u05d1\u05d9\u05e5|url=https://www.globes.co.il/news/article.aspx?did=1001300539|website=\u05d2\u05dc\u05d5\u05d1\u05e1|language=he|access-date=2020-05-10}}</ref>\n*2017 Discovery Award for Team Prismatix (part of UK Longitude Prize Contest) antimicrobial resistance testing technology\n*2016 Hershel Rich Innovation Award\n*2016 Daniel Shiran Memorial Research Prize for outstanding research in biomedicine\n*2015 Yanai Prize for Excellence in Academic Education\n*2014 Henry Taub Award for Academic Excellence\n*2009, 2010, 2011, 2012, 2013, 2014, 2015, 2016, 2017 Technion Excellence in Teaching Award\n\n== Entrepreneurship ==\nSegal serves as the CTO to BactuSense Technologies Ltd and was the project coordinator of Nanopak, an EU-funded project that developed food packaging products in order to extend the shelf life of food.<ref>{{Cite web|title=NanoPack\u2019s Active Food Packaging Shows Impressive Results in Extending Food Shelf Life: (EUFIC)|url=https://www.eufic.org/en/newsroom/article/nanopacks-active-food-packaging-shows-impressive-results-in-extending-food-shelf-life|website=www.eufic.org|access-date=2020-05-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=Home|url=https://www.nanopack.eu/|last=Care|first=Update|website=NanoPack|language=en-US|access-date=2020-05-10}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nSegal is a cancer survivor,<ref>{{Cite web|title=Engineering meets medicine for maximum impact|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/spotlight/engineering-meets-medicine-for-maximum-impact/|last=Society|first=Jennifer Frey-American Technion|website=www.timesofisrael.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-05-10}}</ref> married, and has two children.\n\n== References ==\n{{ref